Genetic Modification
Selective Breeding
That selective breeding involves humans selecting organisms to breed over several generations,
so that a desirable characteristic gets stronger.
That selective breeding has resulted in the edible crops and domesticated animals we have today.
Some of the benets and risks of selective breeding in agriculture and medicine, including ethical
implications (e.g. the health problems caused by inbreeding in selectively bred animals) and
practical implications (e.g. the risks associated with reducing the gene pool).
Tissue Culture
The process of tissue culture in both plants and animals — including the use of a growth medium.
That tissue culture can be used to produce whole plants quickly, cheaply and in very little space.
That tissue culture can also be used to produce identical plants (clones) with desirable
characteristics.
That tissue culture can be used to produce animal cells and tissues for medical research,
allowing scientists to study the cells in isolation, away from systems inside the body.
Genetic Engineering
That during genetic engineering, a gene is transferred from one organism’s genome into another
organism’s genome, in order to introduce a desirable characteristic.
H
The process of genetic engineering, including: the use of restriction enzymes to cut out the desired
gene and cut open the vector DNA leaving unpaired bases (sticky ends), the use of ligase enzymes
to join the gene to the vector DNA and the use of that vector (e.g. a plasmid or virus) to transfer the
desired gene into other cells (e.g. bacteria).
Some of the benets and risks of genetic engineering in agriculture and medicine, including ethical
implications (e.g. genetically engineered animals may suffer from health problems) and practical
implications (e.g. genes from genetically engineered crops may get out into the environment).
Human Population Growth and GM Organisms
That food production needs to increase to meet the demands of a growing human population and
that one way this can be done is through the use of GM crops.
Some of the advantages and disadvantages of using genetic engineering to produce GM crops,
including those associated with the modication of crop plants for insect resistance using a gene
from the bacterium .
Bacillus thuringiensis
That fertilisers can be used to increase food production by improving soil quality and crop growth,
but can also cause environmental problems such as eutrophication.
That biological control can be used to increase food production by reducing the damage caused by
pests without the need for chemical pesticides, but that organisms used in biological control can also
cause problems themselves.
